! Changelog

|!Version |!Date |!Changes |
|v0.1.22 |2026-05-25 |''Fix: setting min/max constraint via cascade prefixed all existing constraints, not just the new one.'' Two related bugs in `kind.computed-constraints-with-valid-picked` + `kind.cascade-set-constraint-num`. ''(a) Chain-prefix bug:'' the new-entry branch was written as `[<valid-picked>!is[blank]] +[addprefix<prefix>]` â€” two separate filter runs. The first accumulated `picked` ("3") onto the already-filtered list ("required"), giving ["required", "3"]. The `+[addprefix<prefix>]` then operated on the FULL accumulator (TW filter `+` prefix = "pipe accumulator through op"), prepending "min:" to BOTH entries â†’ ["min:required", "min:3"]. If the user (mis-)typed the full prefixed form like "min:3" thinking they had to retype the label, the result included a "min:min:3" entry. ''Fix:'' inlined `addprefix<prefix>` into the same operator chain as the new-entry emit: `[<valid-picked>!is[blank]addprefix<prefix>]`. Now the prefix is only applied to the new entry, not the entire accumulator. ''(b) Regex validity guard didn't validate:'' the procedure's outer `<$list filter="[<value>regexp[^[0-9]*$]]">` tried to reject non-digit input but the pattern `^[0-9]*$` contains a `]` inside the bracket-counting filter parser, breaking the regex parse and effectively passing ALL input through. So "min:3" / "abc" / etc. reached the rewrite. ''Fix:'' switched to `<$list filter="[<value>match[]] [<value>compare:integer:gteq[0]] +[first[]]">` â€” `match[]` matches the blank value (clear semantics), `compare:integer:gteq[0]` matches any non-negative integer, +[first[]] coalesces. Non-digit / invalid input now produces an empty filter result, the action no-ops, and the existing constraint stays intact. ''Lesson:'' for TW regex patterns containing `]`, store the pattern in a separate tiddler field and reference via textref `{$:/.../patterns!!name}` â€” the textref is substituted before bracket-counting (same workaround the 0.1.21 url/email/phone work uses for `[^@\s]`). For simple ranges, prefer the `compare:integer:gteq` / `match[]` combo â€” brackets-free. Still open: cascade-palette text-edit row's right-side "(unset)" display for unbound rows is purely cosmetic (the actual value is shown in `ca-name` as "min: 3"); needs a cp engine change to suppress the bound-value column when no bind is declared. Tiddler-only â€” no restart. |
|v0.1.21 |2026-05-25 |''Three new field-types with intrinsic format validation: `url` / `email` / `phone`.'' All three are text-like single-line inputs with HTML5 input semantics (`type="url"` / `type="email"` / `type="tel"` â€” browser-native hints, mobile-keyboard hints on tel). ''`url'':'' checked for `http://` or `https://` prefix via two chained `!prefix` ops on the field value. ''`email'':'' checked via regex `^[^@\s]+@[^@\s]+\.[^@\s]+$` (non-empty local, non-empty domain, â‰¥1 dot, no whitespace, no extra `@`). ''`phone'':'' checked via regex `^(\+49|0)[ 0-9()\/\-]{6,}$` for German numbers (starts with `+49` or `0`, â‰¥6 allowed chars after). ''Regex storage pattern:'' new `_patterns.tid` holds the email + phone-de patterns as FIELDS, referenced via textref `{$:/plugins/rimir/kind/_patterns!!<name>}` â€” the textref form is substituted by the parser BEFORE bracket-counting, so the `[^@\s]` character classes in the patterns don't break filter parsing (see [[tw-gotchas-parser-pragma#Backtick-template operand]]). URL check doesn't need a `_patterns` entry â€” `!prefix[http://]!prefix[https://]` is brackets-free. ''Engine:'' three new viol predicates `kind.viol-format-url` / `-email` / `-phone` (each fires only when typed matches AND value non-blank â€” the existing `required` constraint still handles the empty case independently). All three added to `kind.viol-any` so they block Create in the creator and surface in the validator. `kind.minmax-applicable` extended to include url/email/phone â€” `min:N` / `max:N` now constrain character length on these too. ''Field-input:'' three new dispatch branches in the `<%elseif%>` cascade with HTML5 input types and placeholders (`https://â€¦`, `name@example.com`, `+49 30 12345678`). Three new validation error messages below the input (next to the existing required/min/max/unique/unique:wiki ones). ''Validator:'' three new bulk-report rows with the offending value shown in the detail column. ''Type-builder:'' `<$select>` typed dropdown gains the three new options; `th` tooltip + Raw JSON schema help text updated. ''Cascade-palette:'' three new `try-shape-*` branches in `cascade-helpers.tid` (route through `shape-text-with-typed` â€” cascade rows are single-line text; live format errors only surface in the regular editor, not in cascade-mode text rows). `palette/cascade-helpers.tid` typed picker (Manage kinds â†’ field drill â†’ typed) lists the three new types. ''Common-fields library:'' three new shadow tiddlers `common-fields/{url,email,phone}.tid` tagged `$:/tags/rimir/kind/common-field` â€” appear in the type-builder library dropdown AND the cascade `+ Add field from libraryâ€¦` picker. Icons: ðŸ”— / ðŸ“§ / ðŸ“ž. ''Docs:'' architecture + reference doc tables list new typed values, constraint table notes the intrinsic format check, engine function table lists the new viol predicates. Tiddler-only â€” no JS, no restart. |
|v0.1.20 |2026-05-25 |''Fix: nested JSON-array reads silently returned empty.'' Five helpers built their nested-array reads as `get[kind.fields]jsonget<idx>,[prop]jsonindexes[]` and `:map[â€¦jsonget<idx>,[prop]jsonget<currentTiddler>]` (chain `jsongetâ†’jsonindexes` / `jsongetâ†’jsonget`). The chain returned nothing in practice â€” even though `jsonget<idx>,[prop]` does produce the inner array's JSON string and `jsonindexes[]` should parse it, in the filter chain it always read as empty. ''Symptom:'' the min/max rows in the constraints picker showed "(none)" for fields with `constraints:["required","min:3"]` even though the bound-drill preview on the parent showed `min:3` correctly; 0.1.17 enum-no-options / ref-no-reftypes hints were also emitted whenever typed=enum / typed=ref regardless of actual options / ref-types presence. ''Fix:'' switched to the canonical pattern from `engine.tid:22` (`kind.field-array-flat`): `jsonindexes<idx>,[prop]` walks the path AND returns the indices in one operator; `jsonget<idx>,[prop],<currentTiddler>` reads each value via three-arg path navigation. ''Affected helpers'' (all in `palette/cascade-helpers.tid`): `kind.cascade-current-constraint-num`, `kind.computed-constraints-with-valid-picked`, `kind.cascade-append-constraint` (inline filter inside the procedure), `kind.cascade-issue-enum-no-options`, `kind.cascade-issue-ref-no-reftypes`. After this fix: min/max rows show "min: 3" / "max: (none)" correctly; enum-no-options / ref-no-reftypes only emit when the respective array is genuinely empty. ''Lesson:'' for nested JSON-array walks in TW, never chain `jsongetâ†’jsonindexes`; use `jsonindexes<path>` with the full path in one operator. Tiddler-only â€” no restart. |
|v0.1.19 |2026-05-25 |''Parameterised constraints (`min:N` / `max:N` / custom) in the constraints picker.'' The constraints sub-stage previously offered only the three flag-constraints `required` / `unique` / `unique:wiki` (as toggle rows). Three new rows extend it: two text-edit rows ''min'' (â‰¥, order 100) and ''max'' (â‰¤, order 110) that capture a non-negative integer and write it as `min:N` / `max:N` into the field's `constraints` JSON array, plus a ''+ Add custom constraintâ€¦'' (âœš, order 200) text-edit row that appends any user-typed string (e.g. `regex:[a-z]+`) to the array. ''min/max applicability:'' rows only render when `kind.minmax-applicable` passes â€” typed is text/longtext/number/date/datetime OR cardinality is multi (same gate the engine's `kind.viol-min` / `viol-max` use). ''Custom applicability:'' renders whenever `kind.required-applicable` passes (typed not $title/$calculated/blank). ''Current value surfaced'' in min/max `ca-name`: "min: 5" / "max: (none)" â€” the row's name updates on every render via `kind.cascade-current-constraint-num` which reads existing constraints, filters by prefix, strips prefix, takes first. ''Set semantics:'' the `\procedure kind.cascade-set-constraint-num(target-tid, idx, prefix, value)` filter-rejects non-digit input via `<$list filter="[<value>regexp[^[0-9]*$]]">` (typos silently no-op â€” old value retained); blank input clears the constraint (removes the prefix:* entry); digit input replaces (removes old prefix:* and adds new prefix:value, dedup-safe). The new array is rebuilt via `kind.computed-constraints-with-valid-picked` â€” fetches all constraint values, subtracts those starting with prefix, optionally appends the new prefix:value, quotes each via `kind.quote-string`, joins with commas, wraps in [ ] via `kind.wrap-array`; empty result falls back to `kind.empty-array`. Written via `jsonset:json<idx>,[constraints],<new-array>` against `kind.fields`. ''Append semantics:'' `\procedure kind.cascade-append-constraint(target-tid, idx, value)` appends value to the existing array with `+[unique[]]` dedup; same rebuild + jsonset:json pattern. ''Explicit `value` parameter'' on both procedures (rather than relying on `<picked>` scope inheritance) â€” the row's on-commit transclude passes `value=<<picked>>`. ''Why text-edit rather than drill into a sub-picker:'' min/max are open-ended integers â€” a picker would need to enumerate values; text-edit is more natural. Custom is open-ended by design. ''Toggle picker still shows current state'' for required / unique / unique:wiki, so the constraints sub-stage now has a mix of toggle + text rows in one picker â€” cascade-palette routes Space/Enter per-row by `ca-kind`. ''Deletion of custom constraints'' is not yet supported in cascade â€” user edits `kind.fields` JSON directly via the type-builder tab (or via the `constraints` text-edit row that takes the whole space-separated list when typed=array). New helpers: `kind.cascade-field-minmax-row`, `kind.cascade-minmax-row-with-value`, `kind.cascade-constraint-num-row-build`, `kind.cascade-minmax-applicable-here`, `kind.cascade-minmax-applicable-with-typed`, `kind.cascade-current-constraint-num`, `kind.cascade-field-custom-constraint-row`, `kind.cascade-custom-constraint-row-build`, `kind.computed-constraints-with-valid-picked`. New procedures: `kind.cascade-set-constraint-num`, `kind.cascade-append-constraint`. Requires cascade-palette â‰¥ 0.0.53 for `ca-on-commit`. Tiddler-only â€” no restart. |
|v0.1.18 |2026-05-25 |''Add / delete field syncs `kind.stream-fields`.'' Field additions and removals now keep the stream-fields list (the space-separated key list that drives the inline stream bar on every instance) in sync with `kind.fields`. ''+ Add new field'': the `kind.cascade-finalize-new-field` procedure now also runs `$action-listops` with `+[remove<field-key>] +[append<field-key>]` against `kind.stream-fields` â€” the new key is appended exactly once (idempotent against re-fires). ''+ Add field from library'': `kind.cascade-add-cf-to-kind` already appended the cf-key but allowed duplicates; same `+[remove] +[append]` dedup pattern applied. ''DEL on a field row'' + ''ðŸ—‘ Delete this field'' leaf: both now route through a new `\procedure kind.cascade-delete-field(target-tid, idx)` which captures the field-key via `<$let>` BEFORE the rebuild-without runs, then calls `$action-listops $subfilter="+[remove<field-key>]"` to drop the key from stream-fields. The `<$let>` sequencing matters â€” once `kind.fields` is rebuilt the field-key at <idx> is gone, so the let binding must read it first; `<$let>` evaluates at render time and the variable is captured before any action widget fires. ''Consequence text updated'' on both the DEL hint and the delete-leaf confirm to mention the stream-fields cleanup. ''Action-wikitext de-bloat:'' the inline `<$action-setfield â€¦ kind.fields={{{ [â€¦rebuilt-fields-withoutâ€¦] }}}/>` strings (~30 addsuffix ops each) collapsed to single `<$transclude $variable="kind.cascade-delete-field" target-tid="â€¦" idx="â€¦"/>` calls â€” same procedure-as-action pattern the create-kind / finalize-new-field / add-cf-to-kind flows already use. Net: row-build chain shorter, all four field-mutation paths share one procedure. New helper: `kind.cascade-delete-field`. Tiddler-only â€” no restart. |
|v0.1.17 |2026-05-25 |''Validation hints on field rows.'' Field rows in the Manage-kinds drill now surface schema-level problems via `ca-hint` so the focused row's hint area in cascade-palette flags them inline. Five checks: ''âš  key is empty'' (the `key` JSON property is blank â€” usually a half-finished "+ Add new field"), ''âš  typed is not set'' (the `typed` property is blank â€” rare now that 0.1.16 defaults to text, but still possible via manual JSON edit), ''âš  duplicate key 'X''' (another field in the same kind has the same key â€” silent hazard since the type-builder UI would render both rows side-by-side without obvious warning), ''âš  enum has no options'' (typed=enum but the `options` JSON array is missing or empty â€” broken UX at instance-create time), ''âš  ref has no ref-types'' (typed=ref but the `ref-types` JSON array is missing or empty â€” picker would show no candidate kinds). Multiple issues join with ` Â· `. No issues â†’ empty hint string â†’ cascade-palette shows the default hint UI (none). ''Implementation:'' new helpers `kind.cascade-field-hint` (composes the issue list), `kind.cascade-field-issues` (calls each per-issue function), `kind.cascade-issue-{blank-key,no-typed,dup-key,enum-no-options,ref-no-reftypes}`, plus `kind.cascade-key-has-dup` (cross-references other field-indexes for the same key). Added an intermediate `kind.cascade-field-row-with-typed` layer in the build chain to thread `field-hint` through to `kind.cascade-field-row-build` (now takes 5 args instead of 4). ''Doesn't surface'' instance-level violations (`kind.viol-required` / `-min` / `-max` / `-unique` / `-unique:wiki`) â€” those are per-instance checks that the existing validator tab already shows; the cascade-mode is editing the schema, not instances. Tiddler-only â€” no restart. |
|v0.1.16 |2026-05-25 |''`+ Add new field` defaults typed=text.'' Closes a polish gap from 0.1.12: previously the new field was created with only `{key: "<typed-value>"}` and rendered as `<key> Â· ?` in the field-list until the user drilled in to pick typed. The applicability filters on cardinality / constraints / options / ref-types stayed dormant until then. Now the row uses cascade-palette â‰¥ 0.0.53's `ca-on-commit` to invoke a new `\procedure kind.cascade-finalize-new-field(target-tid, idx)` after the key commit; the procedure runs `$action-setfield` with `kind.fields={{{ [â€¦jsonset<idx>,[typed],[text]] }}}`, so the new entry becomes `{key: "<typed-value>", typed: "text"}`. Field row immediately shows `<key> Â· text`, and the constraints / options drills (gated by `kind.required-applicable`) appear on the next render. ''Why a procedure rather than inline action wikitext:'' same reason as the create-new-kind flow â€” the action wikitext would need three `\"`-escaped attribute values for the jsonset filter, unreadable. ''No bind-tiddler conflict:'' the action references the row's baked-in `<<kind-tid>>` and `<<next-idx>>` (composed via addsuffix at row-build time), independent of cascade-palette's `<<picked>>` variable. ''Hint updated:'' "Type the field key and â†µ to add â€” typed defaults to text; drill into the new row to set caption / typed / constraints". Requires cascade-palette â‰¥ 0.0.53 for `ca-on-commit`. Tiddler-only â€” no restart. |
|v0.1.15 |2026-05-25 |''`+ Create new kindâ€¦` row in Manage-kinds.'' Single-keystroke flow for creating a fresh type-definition tiddler: drill `Manage kinds`, cursor on ''+ Create new kindâ€¦'', Space/Enter â†’ edit mode â†’ type the key (e.g. `widget`) â†’ â†µ â†’ a tiddler at `$:/config/rimir/kind/types/widget` is created with the type-builder's standard defaults (`kind.type=widget`, `kind.icon=ðŸ†•`, `kind.title-formula=[get[parent]][[/]][get[abbrev]]+[join[]]`, `kind.fields=[]`, `kind.stream-fields=""`, `type=text/vnd.tiddlywiki`), and the new kind appears immediately in the kind list above (wiki-change-hook recomputes the stage). User can then drill into it to start adding fields. ''Implementation:'' uses cascade-palette â‰¥ 0.0.53's new `ca-on-commit` row action â€” the text row has no bind-tiddler (pure capture); after the user hits â†µ, `<<picked>>` carries the typed key into a new `\procedure kind.cascade-create-kind(key)` which runs `$action-createtiddler` with `$basetitle=$:/config/rimir/kind/types/<key>`. Wrapped in `<$list filter="[<key>!is[blank]]">` so accidental empty commits are no-ops. ''Why a procedure rather than inline action wikitext:'' the action references `<<picked>>` in three positions ($basetitle, kind.type, plus the no-op guard); inlining via JSON-escaped wikitext gets unreadable. ''Naming collision:'' `$action-createtiddler` uniquifies titles via "" or " 1" / " 2" suffix when the title is taken, so typing an existing key just opens an alternative one â€” no data loss but also no warning. Add a duplicate-check via filter pre-condition if/when needed. ''Deferred:'' parameterised constraints (`min:N` / `max:N` / `custom`) â€” same `ca-on-commit` primitive will work for those next. Tiddler-only â€” no restart on the kind side (cascade-palette JS changed in 0.0.53 â€” restart required there). |
|v0.1.14 |2026-05-25 |''Fix: `+ Add new field` was writing to a phantom tiddler.'' `kind.cascade-add-new-field-build` started its addprefix/addsuffix chain with `[<next-idx>]` as the input value, then `addprefix` put the JSON object prefix BEFORE next-idx â€” so next-idx ended up concatenated to the START of the `ca-bind-tiddler` value. With kind-tid = `$:/config/rimir/kind/types/task` and next-idx = `4`, the resulting bind-tiddler was ''`4$:/config/rimir/kind/types/task`'' â€” a non-existent tiddler. Writes succeeded but went into a phantom tiddler whose file ended up at `my-wiki/tiddlers/4$_/config/rimir/kind/types/task.json` (orphaned). ''Fix:'' restructured the builder to start with `[<kind-tid>]` as input (so kind-tid lands naturally inside `ca-bind-tiddler`) and `addsuffix<next-idx>` where it belongs (inside `ca-bind-path`). Same pattern the other working builders use (`kind.cascade-meta-row`, `kind.cascade-field-prop-row`, etc.). ''Cleanup:'' the user should delete `my-wiki/tiddlers/4$_/` (the orphaned directory) and any other `4$_/â€¦` paths created during the buggy period. Requires cascade-palette â‰¥ 0.0.51 to also stop silently switching kind tiddlers from `.tid` to `.json` on every sub-path edit. Tiddler-only â€” no restart on the kind side. |
|v0.1.13 |2026-05-25 |''DEL on a field row removes that field (uses cascade-palette 0.0.50's new `ca-on-delete`).'' Each field row in the per-kind field-list (`<key> Â· <typed>`, built by `kind.cascade-field-row-build`) now carries `ca-on-delete` + `ca-on-delete-consequence`. DEL on the field row pushes a confirm-stage with "Remove field '<key>' from this kind. Existing instances are NOT touched (the value on each instance becomes orphaned)." â†’ â†µ confirm â†’ fires `<$action-setfield $tiddler="<kind-tid>" kind.fields={{{ [function[kind.rebuilt-fields-without],[<kind-tid>],[<field-idx>]] }}}/>` â€” the same rebuild-by-filter the existing "ðŸ—‘ Delete this field" leaf uses (avoiding the `jsonset[N] on array â†’ sparse object` gotcha). User can now delete a field with two keystrokes (Del â†’ â†µ) instead of having to drill in, scroll down to the delete leaf, and confirm. The drill-in delete leaf stays for discoverability. ''Requires cascade-palette â‰¥ 0.0.50'' for the DEL handler to recognise `ca-on-delete`. Tiddler-only â€” no restart on the kind side (cascade-palette JS changed in 0.0.50 â€” restart required there). |
|v0.1.12 |2026-05-25 |''+ Add new field row in Manage-kinds.'' New ''+ Add new fieldâ€¦'' row (âœš, order 710, fields group) sits next to the ''+ Add field from libraryâ€¦'' leaf at the bottom of the per-kind field list. It's a `ca-kind: text` row that binds straight into the `kind.fields` JSON array at the next free index â€” `ca-bind-tiddler: <kind-tid>`, `ca-bind-field: kind.fields`, `ca-bind-path: <next-idx>,key`. Space â†’ type the key â†’ â†µ writes the new field with just `{key: "<typed-value>"}`; cascade-palette's wiki-change-hook then recomputes the stage so a fresh field row appears and the "+ Add new fieldâ€¦" row's `next-idx` is bumped automatically. Cascade-palette's `writeBoundValue` walks the JSON path and creates the intermediate object â€” the new array element is appended cleanly when `kind.fields` is already a valid JSON array (which it is for every existing kind we surface). ''UX trade-off:'' the new field starts with `typed=undefined` (renders as `<key> Â· ?` in the field-list row); applicability filters drop the cardinality / constraints / options / ref-types drills until typed is set, so the user drills into the new row, picks typed via the existing 9-leaf picker (set in 0.1.9), then the relevant drills appear on next render. Hint reflects this: "Type the field key and â†µ to add â€” then drill into the new row to set typed and other props". ''Why not write a complete default object?'' Text-rows commit via `writeBoundValue` (single sub-path write); they don't fire `ca-actions`. Setting typed=text simultaneously would need either (a) a custom scribetype that wraps the key string into `{key, typed:"text", â€¦}` â€” would require a new JS module in kind, restart, and crosses the kindâ†’scribe layering, or (b) a two-stage flow with a state tiddler and a confirm leaf â€” more keystrokes than the single Space-type-â†µ path. The "?"-placeholder approach matches how cascade-palette already handles partial writes elsewhere (drill in to complete). ''Delete-this-field'' was already wired in 0.1.8 (`kind.cascade-field-delete-row` uses `kind.rebuilt-fields-without` to avoid the `jsonset[N] on array â†’ sparse object` gotcha). New helpers: `kind.cascade-add-new-field-row`, `kind.cascade-add-new-field-build`. Added to `kind.cascade-kind-edit-items` between the library picker and the metadata rows. Tiddler-only â€” no restart. |
|v0.1.11 |2026-05-25 |''Constraints / options / ref-types editing in the per-field stage.'' Three array-valued field-def properties now have cascade-mode editing surfaces, each gated on the field's typed value the same way the type-builder cells are. ''constraints'' â€” drill row (applicable iff typed is not `$title`/`$calculated`, via `kind.required-applicable`); picker stage has toggle rows for `required` / `unique` / `unique:wiki`. Each toggle binds `ca-bind-type: application/x-string-array` + `ca-bind-path: <idx>,constraints` + `ca-true-value: <constraint>`; cascade-palette's existing list-membership toggle semantics (`fireToggle` for STRING_ARRAY_TYPE) adds/removes the value cleanly. ''options'' â€” text-edit row with `ca-bind-type: application/x-string-array` (applicable iff typed=enum), bound to `<idx>,options`. Space â†’ type comma-OR-space-separated values â†’ Enter; the scribetype's `toField` splits on whitespace and writes a real JSON array, `fromField` joins back for display. Free-form to match the type-builder's options cell. ''ref-types'' â€” drill row (applicable iff typed=ref); picker has toggle rows for every existing kind (`[function[kind.types-all]get[kind.type]] +[unique[]sort[]]`). Toggle adds/removes the kind from the field's ref-types array. ''Drill row value display'' â€” when the bound JSON path is an array, cascade-palette's `_renderBoundDrillValue` joins with `, ` for display (e.g. `required, unique` next to the constraints drill). Since the read at the drill level doesn't use string-array bind-type, the raw array reaches the renderer's `Array.isArray` branch â€” gives a nicer comma-separated display than the space-separated form the toggle picker uses internally. ''Deferred:'' parameterised constraints (`min:N` / `max:N` / `custom`) need an extra arg input â€” needs the same text-then-action wiring the create-new-kind / add-new-field flows need. New helpers: `kind.cascade-field-array-prop-row`, `kind.cascade-field-{constraints,options,reftypes}-{drill-row|picker-items}`, `kind.cascade-constraint-applicable`, `kind.cascade-array-toggle-build`. Tiddler-only â€” no restart. |
|v0.1.10 |2026-05-25 |''+ Add field from library: common-fields picker in Manage-kinds.'' New leaf ''+ Add field from libraryâ€¦'' (ðŸ“š, order 700, grouped under fields) sits at the bottom of the per-kind field list. Drilling lists every common-field tiddler tagged `$:/tags/rimir/kind/common-field` ''that isn't already on this kind'' (uses `kind.is-common-field-unused` â€” same filter the type-builder's library dropdown uses). Each common-field row shows ''`<key> Â· <typed>`'' + the field's icon. Picking one appends its `def` JSON to `kind.fields` at the next index AND appends its key to `kind.stream-fields`, then `ca-after-fire: pop`s back to the kind-edit stage so the new field row appears immediately. ''Action wiring:'' since the per-CF leaf needs to read the picked CF's `def` field and the kind's current `kind.fields` length at fire time, the action wikitext can't be a single short `$action-setfield` â€” it needs `<$let>` to compute next-idx + cf-def + cf-key first. The leaf's `ca-actions` therefore calls a new `\procedure kind.cascade-add-cf-to-kind(target-tid, cf-tid)` via `<$transclude $variable="â€¦" target-tid="â€¦" cf-tid="â€¦"/>` with both tids baked in at item-build time. The procedure body is the existing type-builder's add-common-field logic (the `jsonset:json<idx>,<cf-def>` + `+[append<cf-key>]` listops pair) wrapped in a `<$let>`. `invokeViaNavigator` renders the action tree before invokeActions so the transcluded procedure's action widgets fire normally. ''New helpers:'' `kind.cascade-add-from-library-row` (the "+" leaf), `kind.cascade-add-from-library-items` (picker items-from), `kind.cascade-cf-leaf-build` + three sub-helpers (`-with-key`, `-with-typed`, `-with-icon`) that thread cf-key / cf-typed / cf-icon through the chain, and the `kind.cascade-add-cf-to-kind` procedure. Tiddler-only â€” no restart. |
